#git commands

->check version:- git --version
->configuration command:- git config --global user.name "user name"
                          git config --global user.email "email"

->to check config list:- git config --list

->intialise git in folder:- git init
->to add all changes to git :- git add .
->to add specific file cjhange:- git add file_name
->to commit the changes :- git commit -m"message"
->to push on github:- git push

->to know all about commits:- git log

->to checkout to specific commit:- git checkout commit_id


 


-> git stash :- Temporarily shelves (stashes) uncommitted changes, giving you a clean working directory.",When you need to switch branches quickly but aren't ready to commit your current half-done work.

-> git stash pop :- Reapplies the most recently stashed changes and removes them from the stash list.,When you return to your branch and want to resume the work you temporarily shelved.

-> git restore filename :- "Discards local, uncommitted changes in your working directory for a specific file.",When you messed up a file and want to revert it back to the state of your last commit.

-> git restore --stages filename :-"Unstages a file, removing it from the index while keeping your local modifications.",When you accidentally ran git add on a file but aren't ready to commit it yet.

-> git restore --soft HEAD~1 :-Undoes the last commit, but keeps all those changes staged in your index.","When you committed too early (e.g., forgot a file) and want to redo the commit without losing your code."

-> git restore --hard HEAD~1 :- [Destructive] Erases the last commit, the staged index, and all uncommitted local modifications.",When your last commit was a total disaster and you want to completely wipe it out.


